<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-11-29T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-11-29T15:00:00-05:00" n="411" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d411">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7442: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Neville</hi></persName>)<note n="61" xml:id="d411fn61">The same
                                to the Ambassador in China as telegram No. 63, November 29, 2
                                p.m.</note></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-29T15:00:00-05:00">November 29, 1935—3
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>185. Under date November 27 the American Embassy at London telegraphed as
                            follows:</p>
                        <p>[Here follows quotation of first paragraph of telegram No. 595, November
                            27, 1 p.m., printed on <ref target="#pg_448">page 448</ref>.]</p>
                        <p>This morning the British Ambassador here gave us the same
                            information.</p>
                        <p>In neither case was any suggestion made that this Government take similar
                            or any action.</p>
                        <p>Department would welcome any comments which you may feel moved to
                            make.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>